{"input": {"source_code": "@SuppressWarnings(\"unchecked\")\npublic static Map<String, String> deserializeOffsetMap(String lastSourceOffset) throws IOException {\n  Map<String, String> offsetMap;\n  if (lastSourceOffset == null || lastSourceOffset.isEmpty()) {    \n    offsetMap = new HashMap<>();  \n  } else {\n    offsetMap = JSON_MAPPER.readValue(lastSourceOffset, Map.class);  \n  }\n  return offsetMap;\n}\n", "repo_info": {"repo": "streamsets/datacollector", "path": "stagesupport/src/main/java/com/.../OffsetUtil.java", "function_name": "OffsetUtil.deserializeOffsetMap"}}, "output": "The provided code is a static method named `deserializeOffsetMap` in the class `OffsetUtil`. This method takes a single parameter: `lastSourceOffset`, which is of type `String`.\n\nHere's an explanation of what this method does:\n\n1. The method first suppresses unchecked exceptions using `@SuppressWarnings(\"unchecked\")`. This means that it will not throw any warnings related to unchecked or unsafe operations.\n\n2. It declares a variable `offsetMap` of type `Map<String, String>`, which is the data structure we want to return from this function.\n\n3. The method then checks if `lastSourceOffset` is either null or an empty string using an `if` statement:\n   - If `lastSourceOffset` is null or an empty string, it initializes `offsetMap` as a new instance of `HashMap<>`.\n   - If `lastSourceOffset` is not null and not an empty string, the method uses the `JSON_MAPPER` object to deserialize the JSON string into a `Map<String, String>`.\n\n4. Finally, the method returns the `offsetMap`.\n\nThe `JSON_MAPPER` variable used in this code is likely a global variable of type `ObjectMapper`, which is part of the Jackson library and is used for reading and writing JSON data in Java.\n\nIn summary, this function deserializes a string into a map if it's not null or empty. If it is null or empty, it returns an empty map.", "metric": 0.260670731707317}
